e[mask]\n            res = float('inf')\n            subset = mask\n            while subset:\n                res = min(res, max(total_time[subset], dp(mask ^ subset, workers - 1)))\n                subset = (subset - 1) & mask\n            return res\n        \n        return dp((1 << n) - 1, k)\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n\n1. **Bitmask Representation**: We use a bitmask to represent each subset of jobs. For example, if `n` is the number of jobs, then `1 << n` gives us the total number of subsets (including the empty set). Each bit in the bitmask represents whether a job is included in the subset or not.\n\n2. **Precompute Total Time**: We precompute the total time for each subset of jobs and store it in the `total_time` array. This allows us to quickly look up the total time for any subset without recalculating it.\n\n3. **Dynamic Programming with Memoization**: We use a recursive function `dp(mask, workers)` that returns the minimum possible maximum working time for assigning the jobs represented by `mask` to `workers` workers. We use `lru_cache` to memoize the results of this function to avoid redundant calculations.\n\n4. **Subset Iteration**: For each call to `dp(mask, workers)`, we iterate over all subsets of `mask` and recursively calculate the result for the remaining jobs and workers. We use the bitmask operation `(subset - 1) & mask` to iterate over all subsets of `mask`.\n\n5. **Base Case**: If there is only one worker left (`workers == 1`), the result is simply the total time for the remaining jobs (`total_time[mask]`).\n\nThis approach ensures that we efficiently find the optimal assignment of jobs to workers, minimizing the maximum working time.", "estimated_date": 1610236800000}